/** * Title : Wee Little Havroshechka * Collector : Aleksandr Afanas'ev * Translator : Jared and Laura Sprague * Date : 26 October 2010 * Words : 850 * New Tale # : 100 * Old Tale # : 56 * */
You know, on the earth, there are good people and those who are a little worse. Then there are those who don't fear God and don't even feel shame. Wee little Havroshechka was left motherless as a small child with the latter type. These people took her in and fed her but didn't allow her out into God's world. Rather, they put her to work every day. She served, cleaned and answered for all and everything.
Her step-mother had three grown daughters. The oldest's name was One-Eye, the middle daughter's name was Two-Eye, and the youngest's name was Three-Eye. The only thing they did was sit in the entry way and gaze outside. Meanwhile Wee little Havroshechka did their work. She sewed their clothes and spun and wove for them, but never heard one word of kindness. She was only noticed when they wanted someone to abuse!
Once, Wee little Havroshechka went into the field. Embracing her spotted cow, she lay against her neck and related how difficult her life was. "Little mother-cow, they beat me and scold me. They don't feed me. And then they order me not to cry. They gave me 200 pounds of linen to spin, weave, bleach in the sun, and roll. It all must be done by tomorrow."
The cow replied, "Beautiful maiden, climb in one of my ears and climb out the other, and all of your work will be done." And so it was. As soon as the beautiful maiden climbed out of the cow's ear everything was ready - woven, washed and rolled.
She carried it to her step-mother who shut it away in a trunk with a grunt. She then gave her even more work to do. Havroshechka came again to the cow. She climbed in one ear and out the other, carrying the completed things back.
The old woman was amazed. She called One-Eye, "My wonderful daughter, my lovely daughter! Find out who helps the orphan. Who weaves, spins and rolls the linen?"
One-Eye went with the orphan through the forest and into the field. She forgot her mother's instructions, became fatigued in the sun, and sprawled out in the grass.
Havroshechka coaxed, "Sleep, little eye. Sleep, little eye!"
One-Eye's one little eye fell asleep. While One-Eye slept, the little cow did the weaving and washing. As the step-mother didn't learn anything from One- Eye, she sent Two-Eye. Two-Eye also became fatigued in the sun, sprawled out in the grass, forgot her mother's instructions, and closed her eyes. Havroshechka sang, "Sleep, little eye. Sleep, other little eye!" The cow did the weaving, washing, and rolling all while Two-Eye's two eyes slept.
The old woman was angry. On the third day she sent Three-Eye and gave the orphan even more work to do. And just like her older sisters, she bounded along and eventually fell into the grass. Havroshechka sang, "Sleep, little eye. Sleep, other little eye!" But she forgot about Three-Eye's third little eye. Two eyes fell asleep, while the third watched and saw everything: from the beautiful maiden climbing in one ear and out the other and then gathering up all the prepared linens. Three-Eye told her mother everything she saw.
The old woman rejoiced. On the very next day she came to her husband, "Slaughter that spotted cow!"
The old man was reluctant. "What are you saying, woman? Are you out of your mind? That cow is young and healthy!"
But she was absolutely determined. So, he sharpened the knife.
Havroshechka ran to the cow. "Little cow-mother! They want to slaughter you."
"Don't eat my meat, beautiful maiden. Gather my bones, tie them in a handkerchief, then plant them in the garden, and never forget me. Water my bones every morning."
Havroshechka did everything as the cow instructed. She endured great hunger, but still didn't eat any meat. She watered the bones in the garden every day, from which an apple tree grew. Goodness, what a tree it was! The apples were plump. The rustling leaves were golden. The bowing branches were silver. Whoever rode by stopped to look at the tree. Whoever walked by would stare in wonder.
One day the girls were strolling in the garden when a nobleman rode through the field. He was wealthy, handsome, and young. Seeing the apples, he got the girls' attention. "Maiden-beauties!" he said, "whoever can bring me an apple will be my wife."
And so the three sisters pushed themselves in front of each other to get to the apple tree. While before the apples hung lower than arm's height, suddenly they were oh so high, to the point that they were far above their heads. The sisters wanted to knock them off the tree, but the leaves blinded them. They wanted to pick the apples, but the branches unpicked their braids. No matter how they struggled and thrashed about, tearing their hands, they still couldn't pick any apples.
Havroshechka came to the tree. The branches bowed down and apples drooped into her reach. The nobleman married her. They lived in happiness, without any sorrow.

metaRep.metaDesc: Would we consider this a generic? A: Is this sending her to a workplace or a verb? J: Less a workplace and more like toil. Conclusion: Do not mark it.
Would we consider this a generic? Is this sending her to a workplace or a verb? J: Less a workplace and more like toil.
Is there any reason to separate them out? No, since they are synonyms (all and everything), we can keep it one phrase.
When there is a measured amount of a thing, we do not need to mark the thing, just the whole quantity. Ex: "200 pounds of linen" "a measure of walnuts"

There was some question as to whether "outside" refers to the outside generally or is just a particle attached to the verb. "Outside" is, in this case, a distinct place. But we also decided that it is irrelevant to the marking of the referring expression generally, and, like the direction "to the 'north'" we would mark it anyway.
Is the "kindness" in "one word of kindness" similar to "rye" in cake of "rye" (which we do not mark)? "Kindness" is necessary to the referring expression, which could also be "any kindness."

Is this a generic? Do they want a specific person to abuse or would they settle for anyone? Conclusion: Someone fills that position, so it is not generic, and we would coreference with the lucky abused.
When we have a phrase like "all of your work," would we separate the quantifier from the quantified? What to do when the part equals the whole? Don't separate. Leave it one referring expression.

Since this is the same person, should we separate them or keep them togeher? Arguments: Since the weaving, spinning, and rolling are sub-activities under the helping of the orphan, it seems fine to keep them all together. Mark says that in the case of "Mary gave it to John. He..." we would mark "John" and "he" separately. Conclusion: Separate them.

In cases like this, we could paraphrase as "the step-mother learned not anything" or "the step-mother learned nothing," which would make marking "n't...anything" desirable, but for consistency's sake, we mark only "anything."
Include the "woman," because we treat it like an apositive.

In this case, the referring expression is the words of the instructions and not the statement itself, so we have not included the quotation marks. Still unclear on whether we should include the periods.
"put to work" is in the dictionary
not in the dictionary but it made more sense to me to put them together.
